  <text>
      <body>
         
        <p>Written after first hearing of the formation of Ladies' Anti-Slavery Associations.</p>
         
         <lg>
         <l>Slavery! silent hopeless anguish­--</l>
         <l>British souls have felt thy care:</l>
         <l>Yet their firmest efforts languish</l>
         <l>Into all the slave's despair.</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Is there hope?--The thought were glory,</l>
         <l>Piercing through a darksome cave:</l>
         <l>Statesmen, poets, tell thy story,</l> 
         <l>Yet is found no hand to save.</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Is there hope? Yes, if exerted,</l>
         <l>One untried, resistless power,</l>
         <l>Modest, quiet, unasserted,</l>
         <l>Patient through the darkest hour.</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Sisters:--ye whose tears have glistened</l>
         <l>At the tale of Afric's woe;</l>
         <l>Let the sympathy that listened</l>
         <l>All its energy bestow.</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Gentle hands by thousands aiding,</l> 
         <l>Eloquence, though soft as lutes,</l>
         <l>By ten thousand lips persuading,</l> 
         <l>Can secure your high pursuits.</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Shall a gust of blessings reach us,</l>
         <l>Poured from grateful negro-tongues,</l>
         <l>While their generous virtues teach us</l> 
         <l>Negroes can forget their wrongs?</l></lg>
         
         <lg><l>Yes, the western breeze shall bear it­-</l>
         <l>Yes, the triumph shall be true!</l>
         <l>Sister-Britons, ye shall share it,­-</l>
         <l>Heaven reserves the bliss for you!</l></lg>
         
         <signed>D. Ball</signed>
         
      </body>
  </text>
